Practice until it sounds good. Then break it again so it sounds bad. Wash, rinse, repeat.

When I'm working on something new, it's bad. Like, it's really bad. It's like I have never touched a drum sometimes.

And I sound AWFUL.

When I work on new material, I sound so bad that my buddy who was working on my house (and is also a musician) interrupted my practice session to find out why I sounded so bad (he's a good friend and we laughed about it). In his words "you usually sound like a metronome but this just sounds horrible."

I wish I could say that was the first time that happened to me. It used to happen a lot in college actually. I had one friend open the practice room door and say "you sound awful, what are you doing".

And I love it.

It is frustrating and maddening and depressing and exhilarating and fun.

If you don't love the process, this is gonna be a long life for you.

So what are you going to sound bad at today?

#drums #drummer #drumlesson #Tuesday

There was a time when I listened to so much music during the day that I would have to stop because my ears were just tired. They couldn't listen anymore.

Try this and see what happens in your playing.

1. Pick an artist or style of music you have never listened to.

2. Pick 5 albums by that artist or in that style.

3. Listen to NOTHING but those albums, on repeat, for 30 days. As much as you can listen to them. While you're eating, while you're driving, while you're working, while you're working out, while you're falling asleep...you get the idea.

4. Try isolating each instrument within the song on different listens and hear exactly what they are playing.

5. Attempt to play along to some of the songs once you understand them enough.

6. Memorize and sing the different parts being played.

7. Dissect what the lyrics mean.

The internet has somehow successfully separated our craft from its source. Drums, for me, mean NOTHING without music.

Instead of spending time surfing social media, becoming enraged with how seemingly bad the world is, or wasting time in any other number of ways...make your personal world 100x better by LISTENING TO MORE MUSIC. It will make you a better person and a better musician. We change the world by changing ourselves first. Music can be a big part of that personal change.

"Without music, life would be a blank to me." -Jane Austen

Let's start 2023 off right with some truth. Because I want you to succeed, to be happy, and to thrive with music and drumming.

It’s a sad day when the fundamentals of our craft are referred to as “boring”, “ordinary”, and “lacking in style”.

If I see one more one handed roll or chopsing over a song post with no musical purpose, I think I’m gonna throw up.

Should we strive to be great at our craft?

Yes.

Should we gather all of the tools we can and learn as much as possible?

Absolutely.

Should we learn how to use these tools musically?

YES.

You see, there is NOTHING wrong with pushing the boundaries of your skills and learning everything you can. However, far too often I see the MUSIC sacrificed for the sake of using a tool on the instrument just because we have it. Oftentimes, the tools we need for a situation are simply ignored because they showcase the MUSIC instead of showcasing US...but showcasing the music IS THE POINT. In our need to gratify ourselves, our ego, our virtuosity we lose the music. Tools like groove, dynamics, articulation, phrasing, musicality, situational awareness, humility...these are not flashy tools. But they are the core of music.

And you don't need an award or nomination to know you're doing a good job. It's better if we do good work for the sake of good work with no need for affirmation from a popularity contest.

I posted this a while back, but it's still very relevant in our time of 15 second drum clips.

#monday
#music #playthesong #leavethetricksathome #pocketisking

As a teacher, this is a really hard lesson to teach.

Because it's more about the internal stuff (who we are) rather than the external stuff (the things we play on our instrument).

Those two things WILL work together if we will get out of the way and let them.

This exercise has helped me over the years learn more about who I am as a player. That's knowledge we can carry into every situation to help the music.

I think this is more photos of my family than I have ever posted. I typically like to keep my personal life just that...personal. But...it's Father's Day and I'm not able to be with them. So I'm having coffee and breakfast thinking about how blessed I am. About to open a package they snuck into my suitcase. They're the best.

I had a great father. He was a man and he had his own demons he struggled with, but we all do. When it came to being a father though, he did a great job. So I feel like I started this whole journey ahead of where I should have started it by having a good example. A good example in what to do, what not to do, areas I can mimic, areas I can improve on what he did. We teach just as much through our mistakes and faults as we do through our successes. Maybe more even.

So, these are pics of my people.

Brooklyn is 6. Her favorite colors are pink and rainbow. Her favorite animals are unicorns and mermaids. She is quite possibly the most girlie girl to ever exist. She's growing a bean plant in a pot outside and keeps talking about "the harvest". She loves school, gymnastics, and time at home. We recently built some home made shakers together and when I asked her which one had the best sound, she said "I'll have to wait and see which one sound controls my brain".

Carter is 12. If you have ever had the privilege of being around Carter, you've seen bottled electricity in human form. He has more energy than I've ever had in my life. He loves drawing, football, video games, and electronics. He was a leader at VBS last week and KILLED it.

Jackson is 15. He absolutely loves people. Any people. He recently got his driver's permit and his first job at Chik Fil A. He opened a mutual fund with his own money 2 years ago. He is the consumate deal maker. He's volunteered with the special needs program at our church for the past 2 years.

Then there's my partner in crime, Kelli. She has incredibly high expectations of me as a father and won't hesitate to call me on my own bs. She's also spent countless hours up late at night talking about our kids with me.

Happy Father's Day to all you out there. Here's to the most challenging adventure you'll ever go on.

Look, I love nerding out and practicing the hard stuff. But so often in my teaching, I simply need to HOOK someone on the drums...especially beginners. They HAVE to have an early win. There is no bigger win than playing a song. The gap from not being able to play music to actually playing music seems HUGE, but the leap isn't that bad. I can have a new student up and playing a song the first day. And this is a massive win for anyone.

Once we as teachers hook the student, you don't have to beg them to practice. They WANT to practice. So in my teaching, I lead with MUSIC. My goal is to have students up and playing a song asap.

Yes, let's teach technique and chops and linear and 4 way coordination and odd time signatures andandand...but if you're struggling for motivation in your practice time, try picking out a few easy songs you love but have never learned. When you're done, I promise, you're gonna be in a different mental space. Practice is all about daily wins.

True story.

For the last year and a half I've been out on the road with The Steel Woods. I think I've played around 115 shows with them in that time. I always appreciate the opportunity to make good music and be involved with solid projects. It's an honor each time. With as much as I've enjoyed my time, 2024 is bringing a new direction for me and I will no longer be with them. I want to extend a huge thank you to the Steel Woods crew for having me out. A huge thank you to the fans for welcoming me into the fold and for all of the energy, kindness, and good times this past year and a a half. For every fan that I had the opportunity to meet, for every student that came out to the show, to every person I had the opportunity to eat food or drink coffee or share a laugh, to every musician I got the privilege to hang with...thank you. It felt like literally every town we pulled into I had friends there waiting to hang, have dinner, or share a drink. To play good music, to laugh with others, to share the ups and downs this industry brings with friends...a guy can't ask for much more than that. If you get the chance, go out and see them this year and tell 'em hey for me! Supporting live music is a thing we should all be doing.

Here's to 2024...New music coming, new shows are already booked, Drum camps are selling out, and I've got a ton of teaching planned. It's gonna be a great year!
